"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%\"xG\"\"\",&F$F%F%F%F%,**$)F$\"\"$F%F%*$)F$\"\"#F
%!\"\"F$F%F-F.F%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where Maple did not find \+
enough linear factors, there is a reason why Maple did not.  Maple mak
es an assumption that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all give
n exactly (as integers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), then \+
you are only interested in finding exact factors (factors where the co
efficients are integers or rational numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem
 of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the factors of  a polynomial will n
ecessarily have the same kind of coefficients as the polynomial, only \+
the polynomial can be factored.  You can force Maple to report additio
nal (approximate) factors.  For example,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" 
}}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F
&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,s
qrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&
\"\"#!\"\"F&,&F%F&F'F&F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is the difference?  The extra-te
rm is called a " }{TEXT 280 18 "field extension.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Add
ing it tells Maple to consider additonal factors where the coefficient
s are allowed to include elements from the field extension.  It is fai
rly clear from the factoriztion of " }{TEXT 281 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " \+
all by itself that something involving  sqrt(5)  would have to be incl
uded.  However, there are problems where there is not a obvious clue a
s to which specific field extension should be added.  If you are willi
ng to accept an appropriate solution, then using the field extension \+
" }{TEXT 282 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " tells Maple to factor the polyno
mial using a floating point approximation scheme.  For example, consid
er (here I am pretending I don't see that adding  sqrt(5) would be opt
imal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"
xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#
*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"
\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "
Finally, the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra does not guarantee that a \+
polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 283 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }
{TEXT 284 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 " real linear factors.  Rather, only hat \+
it will have " }{TEXT 285 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 134 " linear factors.  What \+
is the difference?  Some of the factors may involve complex roots rath
er than real roots.  For example compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7!\"\"F),&F%F)F*
F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7F)F),
&F'F)*&F(F)\"\"$#F)F(!\"\"F),&F'F)*&F(F)F-F.F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(F,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
