{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 31 "Note:  it is possible to use a " }{TEXT 
291 9 "for loop " }{TEXT -1 69 " to simplify this task since we are do
ing a repetitive calculation.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 29 "Note: \+
 Also, the the command " }{TEXT 293 6 "coeffs" }{TEXT -1 15 " unfortun
ately " }{TEXT 294 8 "does not" }{TEXT -1 36 " pick off the coefficien
ts in order." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 4 "The " }{TEXT 260 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 66 " gives a fo
rmula for finding the coefficients of the expansion of " }{XPPEDIT 18 
0 "(a+b)^n;" "6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 10 "  for any " 
}{TEXT 295 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obvious that the co
efficient of  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^k*b^(n-k);" "6#*&)%\"aG%\"kG\"\"\")%
\"bG,&%\"nGF'F&!\"\"F'" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value of " }{TEXT 296 
1 "k" }{TEXT -1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 297 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 46 " is gi
ven by the number of ways we can choose " }{TEXT 298 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 
8 " of the " }{TEXT 300 1 "a" }{TEXT -1 12 "'s from the " }{TEXT 299 
1 "n" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 301 1 "a" }{TEXT -1 20 "'s in the expansi
on " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)*(a+b)" "6#*&,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&F&,&F%F&F'F
&F&" }{TEXT -1 7 " ....( " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)" "6#,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"b
GF%" }{TEXT -1 4 " ), " }{TEXT 302 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 41 " times .   The \+
number of combinations of " }{TEXT 303 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 18 " objects ch
oosing " }{TEXT 304 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 12 " at a time, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "
nCk" "6#%$nCkG" }{TEXT -1 27 ", is given by the formula  " }{XPPEDIT 
18 0 "nCk=n!/(k!*(n-k)!)" "6#/%$nCkG*&-%*factorialG6#%\"nG\"\"\"*&-F'6
#%\"kGF*-F'6#,&F)F*F.!\"\"F*F2" }{TEXT -1 2 " ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 262 10 "State the " }{TEXT 261 
16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 305 31 "and use Maple to \+
demonstrate it" }{TEXT -1 1 "." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 8 "Compute " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "sum(binomial(n,k
),k=0..n)" "6#-%$sumG6$-%)binomialG6$%\"nG%\"kG/F*;\"\"!F)" }{TEXT -1 
34 "  for n=1 to 10.  Here the symbol " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "Sigma;" "6#%&S
igmaG" }{TEXT -1 70 " (Greek letter Sigma) stands for sum.   (See the \+
worksheet SumSeq.mws)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "for n from 1 to 10" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 3 " do" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 19 "  for k from
 0 to n" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 5 "   do" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "    binomial(n,k)" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 10 "   end do;" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 " end do;" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
259 59 "What general formula do the above calculations in  suggest?" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 388 "5.  Pas
cal's Triangle.  Recall the definition of Pascal's Triangle.   Use Map
le to construct the first 10 rows of Pascal's Triangle. (The trick wil
l be to get the coefficients to occur in the correct order.  The Maple
 command for generating a sequence might be helpful. It is   seq(expre
ssion(i),i=m..n);   where expression(i) is an expression with index i \+
and m..n is a range of numbers." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "for p from 0 to 10" }}{PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 45 " do seq(coeff(expand((a+1)^p),a,k), k=0..
p );" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "od;" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"\"" }
